00:01:05.620 --> 00:01:09.170
It basically covers all your
content from games to apps,

00:01:09.170 --> 00:01:11.580
music, books, movies,
and magazines.

00:01:11.580 --> 00:01:13.450
It's the place where you
get your content.

00:01:13.450 --> 00:01:16.490
It's the place where
you enjoy it.

00:01:16.490 --> 00:01:19.220
So today we're going to be
talking about the redesign.

00:01:19.220 --> 00:01:21.280
Particularly, there are three
key words that are going to go

00:01:21.280 --> 00:01:25.150
across the presentation, is how
we design it responsive,

00:01:25.150 --> 00:01:27.700
how we made it responsive,
modular, and

00:01:27.700 --> 00:01:31.490
emotional at the same time.

00:01:31.490 --> 00:01:35.300
So we had three goals in mind
when we redesigned the Google

00:01:35.300 --> 00:01:38.570
Play suite of applications.

00:01:38.570 --> 00:01:42.440
One was to create consistency
across Play, to populate

00:01:42.440 --> 00:01:45.850
content dynamically, and to
create efficient layout on web

00:01:45.850 --> 00:01:47.100
and device.

00:01:49.460 --> 00:01:52.150
So creating consistency.

00:01:52.150 --> 00:01:55.770
Basically, if you have been
using Google Play in the past,

00:01:55.770 --> 00:01:58.160
you would have seen that we had
a lot of different ways to

00:01:58.160 --> 00:01:59.770
represent content.

00:01:59.770 --> 00:02:04.190
And we thought that we sort of
needed to make it uniform in

00:02:04.190 --> 00:02:07.430
order to create an experience
that felt familiar to people.

00:02:10.430 --> 00:02:13.940
Populate content dynamically
means that while we had ways

00:02:13.940 --> 00:02:17.490
to display content in a dynamic
way across devices and

00:02:17.490 --> 00:02:20.450
web, there were certain types
of content, particularly

00:02:20.450 --> 00:02:23.230
collections, that couldn't
be displayed dynamically.

00:02:23.230 --> 00:02:26.060
For example, you will remember
those tiles that were

00:02:26.060 --> 00:02:28.630
promoting different collections
of content.

00:02:28.630 --> 00:02:31.430
Those tiles had to be
manually drawn,

00:02:31.430 --> 00:02:33.570
generated, exported in JPEGs.

00:02:33.570 --> 00:02:39.080
And so we couldn't either
propose content based on your

00:02:39.080 --> 00:02:41.720
preferences, collection based on
your preferences because we

00:02:41.720 --> 00:02:43.970
had to produce those
tiles beforehand.

00:02:43.970 --> 00:02:46.685
And also it was a very labor
intensive process.

00:02:50.500 --> 00:02:52.790
When we talk about efficient
layout, it's not about the

00:02:52.790 --> 00:02:55.390
layout being efficient,
but it's rather make

00:02:55.390 --> 00:02:57.070
our work more efficient.

00:02:57.070 --> 00:03:00.010
So we had to design for a lot
of different screens and

00:03:00.010 --> 00:03:02.390
platforms, including the web.

00:03:02.390 --> 00:03:08.030
And we just wanted to have a
system so that designers could

00:03:08.030 --> 00:03:13.550
define and design their layouts
once and apply them to

00:03:13.550 --> 00:03:14.400
all platforms.

00:03:14.400 --> 00:03:16.460
So we could focus more on the
new features and the cool

00:03:16.460 --> 00:03:18.890
stuff rather than translating
the same thing

00:03:18.890 --> 00:03:20.140
over and over again.

00:03:23.330 --> 00:03:26.150
So let's jump into the solution
and the design

00:03:26.150 --> 00:03:32.200
principles that took us
through this journey.

00:03:32.200 --> 00:03:34.700
So everything starts
with cards.

00:03:34.700 --> 00:03:37.540
The interesting thing about
cards is that it is this

00:03:37.540 --> 00:03:40.720
[INAUDIBLE] element that
defines an entity, that

00:03:40.720 --> 00:03:42.490
defines an object.

00:03:42.490 --> 00:03:47.150
And so rather than designing
grids, which is a sort of

00:03:47.150 --> 00:03:49.800
outside in approach where you
have grids and you put stuff

00:03:49.800 --> 00:03:53.780
in it, we thought about cards
being this [INAUDIBLE] element

00:03:53.780 --> 00:03:56.590
that creates spaces from
the inside out.

00:03:56.590 --> 00:04:00.670
So multiple cards shows up on
your layout and define the

00:04:00.670 --> 00:04:02.380
content that you see.

00:04:02.380 --> 00:04:05.320
Let me get into some examples.

00:04:05.320 --> 00:04:08.850
So a card is great because,
like I said, it contains

00:04:08.850 --> 00:04:13.270
objects, whether they are
applications or albums or

00:04:13.270 --> 00:04:18.660
movies or magazines or books
or even people or

00:04:18.660 --> 00:04:20.390
artists and so forth.

00:04:20.390 --> 00:04:24.740
They basically can contain any
type of thing and by being in

00:04:24.740 --> 00:04:28.100
the same module, we are able to
display things next to each

00:04:28.100 --> 00:04:33.180
other, no matter what kind
of entity they are.

00:04:33.180 --> 00:04:36.650
The other great property that
cards have is the ability to

00:04:36.650 --> 00:04:38.290
be in different shapes.

00:04:38.290 --> 00:04:41.450
So we design a lot of different
cards so that the

00:04:41.450 --> 00:04:44.040
[INAUDIBLE] could be more
interesting and hierarchical.

00:04:44.040 --> 00:04:49.320
So we had what we call tiny
cards or small cards or big

00:04:49.320 --> 00:04:52.550
cards, and cards can also
be displayed in multiple

00:04:52.550 --> 00:04:54.960
orientations in order to
accommodate different layouts.

00:04:54.960 --> 00:04:59.060
We also have what we call a
medium card or a list view

00:04:59.060 --> 00:05:01.670
type of card.

00:05:01.670 --> 00:05:05.280
So there are two things that
having different sizes

00:05:05.280 --> 00:05:06.560
accommodate for.

00:05:06.560 --> 00:05:08.460
One is that they create
hierarchy.

00:05:08.460 --> 00:05:10.450
They can show things to be more

00:05:10.450 --> 00:05:12.030
important by being bigger.

00:05:12.030 --> 00:05:14.670
And also to accommodate for
different informational

00:05:14.670 --> 00:05:17.800
purposes, meaning they can have
more or less white space

00:05:17.800 --> 00:05:20.230
in them to show more or
less information.

00:05:20.230 --> 00:05:23.500
For example, in the store, when
we find something that

00:05:23.500 --> 00:05:26.810
you maybe like, we put in a
bigger card which has a bigger

00:05:26.810 --> 00:05:29.920
info area in order for display
more reasons about why you may

00:05:29.920 --> 00:05:32.970
like it, or maybe we can
display people that

00:05:32.970 --> 00:05:34.550
+1 it and so forth.

00:05:34.550 --> 00:05:37.290
And same we do on other
applications and you'll see

00:05:37.290 --> 00:05:38.540
that in music later.

00:05:41.340 --> 00:05:44.190
Another key element of our
design are canvasses.

00:05:44.190 --> 00:05:48.610
So once you understand cards,
you also understand how your

00:05:48.610 --> 00:05:52.110
application is basically just
a canvas on top of which

00:05:52.110 --> 00:05:53.670
elements are displayed.

00:05:53.670 --> 00:05:57.540
So it doesn't matter if the
canvas is the store or music

00:05:57.540 --> 00:05:58.430
or whatnot.

00:05:58.430 --> 00:06:01.080
The point is that you have
content that is displayed on

00:06:01.080 --> 00:06:02.550
top of these canvases.

00:06:02.550 --> 00:06:07.290
Somehow our design tries to be
APK agnostic in a way that you

00:06:07.290 --> 00:06:10.620
may see in the future a book
in the music application.

00:06:10.620 --> 00:06:11.140
Why not?

00:06:11.140 --> 00:06:14.420
The store is a perfect example
where all the content come

00:06:14.420 --> 00:06:16.065
together in one place.

00:06:18.950 --> 00:06:21.600
Another great example of
canvases is what we do today

00:06:21.600 --> 00:06:23.450
in the movies application.

00:06:23.450 --> 00:06:27.480
If you're familiar with it, when
you pause a movie, you

00:06:27.480 --> 00:06:29.670
basically see the actor
that is there.

00:06:29.670 --> 00:06:32.670
You see similar movies where
the actor has been

00:06:32.670 --> 00:06:34.140
participating in.

00:06:34.140 --> 00:06:36.330
And this is just a canvas.

00:06:36.330 --> 00:06:39.140
It is a canvas where we display
on top of it a person

00:06:39.140 --> 00:06:42.870
card and a list view card with
a bunch of movies in it.

00:06:42.870 --> 00:06:46.180
It just about canvases the
content lives on top of them.

00:06:48.780 --> 00:06:51.570
Another notion that is
key to our design is

00:06:51.570 --> 00:06:53.340
the notion of clusters.

00:06:53.340 --> 00:06:57.860
So once you have multiple cards
next to each other,

00:06:57.860 --> 00:07:01.590
because of the visual psychology
law of proximity,

00:07:01.590 --> 00:07:04.420
you perceive it as one
unit, a cluster.

00:07:04.420 --> 00:07:09.320
And that allows us to display
collections in this way.

00:07:09.320 --> 00:07:12.780
We also made these collections
to be dynamic and follow that

00:07:12.780 --> 00:07:16.290
hierarchy that I talked about
before by allowing a cluster

00:07:16.290 --> 00:07:18.480
to have different
models in them.

00:07:18.480 --> 00:07:21.665
And because we designed those
cards beforehand to be plugged

00:07:21.665 --> 00:07:25.470
in to each other through
heights, they are following

00:07:25.470 --> 00:07:27.210
the same structure.

00:07:27.210 --> 00:07:29.720
We can basically display
clusters that have different

00:07:29.720 --> 00:07:32.490
types of cards in them
and still feel as a

00:07:32.490 --> 00:07:34.710
unit, as you see here.

00:07:34.710 --> 00:07:39.670
Also naturally, the clusters
they work across our typical

00:07:39.670 --> 00:07:48.730
canvases like phones, or
tablets, and web and beyond.

00:07:48.730 --> 00:07:52.600
This led us into this responsive
layout philosophy.

00:07:52.600 --> 00:07:55.230
When we talk about responsive
layout, we're talking more

00:07:55.230 --> 00:07:57.340
about a design approach,
rather than the

00:07:57.340 --> 00:07:59.130
responsive web designer.

00:07:59.130 --> 00:08:02.430
So we're not talking about
designing your website to

00:08:02.430 --> 00:08:06.230
respond to different canvases,
but rather how as designers we

00:08:06.230 --> 00:08:08.930
thought about how our layouts
will expand across multiple

00:08:08.930 --> 00:08:10.120
screen sizes.

00:08:10.120 --> 00:08:13.070
And this is what we define here
as responsible layout and

00:08:13.070 --> 00:08:14.640
responsive design.

00:08:14.640 --> 00:08:17.530
So as you see, we took into
consideration all the typical

00:08:17.530 --> 00:08:25.350
canvases from phones to tablet,
seven inch, to tablet

00:08:25.350 --> 00:08:29.170
10 inches, and typical
laptops.

00:08:29.170 --> 00:08:32.000
We always had all those canvases
in mind and we kept

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:34.220
on designing throughout
these canvases

00:08:34.220 --> 00:08:35.620
across the whole process.

00:08:35.620 --> 00:08:38.890
We didn't start from phone or
from a particular tablet.

00:08:38.890 --> 00:08:41.875
The process took us through all
these canvases, and all we

00:08:41.875 --> 00:08:45.530
were thinking about was how
many columns these layouts

00:08:45.530 --> 00:08:46.910
will be supported on.

00:08:46.910 --> 00:08:48.080
It's just a number of columns.

00:08:48.080 --> 00:08:51.770
We ended up almost not calling
phones phones anymore, but

00:08:51.770 --> 00:08:55.000
just calling them four inches
or three inches or maybe two

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:57.530
columns layout, three columns
layout, et cetera.

00:09:01.420 --> 00:09:04.530
Let's get into the output a
little bit and then we will

00:09:04.530 --> 00:09:08.160
jump into music which is a great
example of how these

00:09:08.160 --> 00:09:10.700
principles are applied
in practice.

00:09:10.700 --> 00:09:14.820
But some examples that I want to
show in these layouts are,

00:09:14.820 --> 00:09:18.800
for instance, this is the store
and you can see how the

00:09:18.800 --> 00:09:21.830
same types of cluster scales
across all screens.

00:09:21.830 --> 00:09:25.300
In particular, this particular
movie is recommended to me

00:09:25.300 --> 00:09:27.750
bigger because a friend
of +1 it.

00:09:27.750 --> 00:09:32.330
And you see how its prominence
hierarchy is scaled across

00:09:32.330 --> 00:09:37.180
phone, a seven inch, and a ten
inch tablet, growing in size,

00:09:37.180 --> 00:09:40.540
and allowing other content to
display next to it by keeping

00:09:40.540 --> 00:09:42.570
that hierarchical
relationship.

00:09:42.570 --> 00:09:45.540
On phone you don't see other
content part of the same

00:09:45.540 --> 00:09:48.500
cluster just because the space
doesn't allow that, but when

00:09:48.500 --> 00:09:51.630
you get to the 10 inch tablet
instead, we have a very

00:09:51.630 --> 00:09:55.080
beautiful big cover with other
related content next to it

00:09:55.080 --> 00:09:56.330
which is recommended to me.

00:09:59.470 --> 00:10:02.340
When we're talking about
modularity, we also applied

00:10:02.340 --> 00:10:06.800
the same principles in the store
in the way we show our

00:10:06.800 --> 00:10:09.740
banners, in the way we apply
our photography to our

00:10:09.740 --> 00:10:10.760
collections.

00:10:10.760 --> 00:10:14.640
For example, here you see that
we have an author photos next

00:10:14.640 --> 00:10:18.160
to the content and you see how
we show more or less content

00:10:18.160 --> 00:10:21.010
according to the number of
columns supported by the

00:10:21.010 --> 00:10:22.330
particular device.

00:10:22.330 --> 00:10:25.410
And you also see how the photo
shifts a little bit.

00:10:25.410 --> 00:10:28.960
So on phone, it shifts a little
bit to the left in

00:10:28.960 --> 00:10:31.710
order to always be centered
in that particular place.

00:10:31.710 --> 00:10:34.890
But this responsive layout,
this efficiency, is also

00:10:34.890 --> 00:10:38.500
applied to the way we started
producing these assets, these

00:10:38.500 --> 00:10:39.240
photography.

00:10:39.240 --> 00:10:43.050
It is always a 16 by 9 photo
that scales and moves a little

00:10:43.050 --> 00:10:46.160
bit across all devices.

00:10:46.160 --> 00:10:48.695
And the same is true even
for our banners.

00:10:52.250 --> 00:10:54.970
Finally, about familiarity.

00:10:54.970 --> 00:10:56.980
Like I said before, we
want to be as much as

00:10:56.980 --> 00:10:58.760
possible APK agnostic.

00:10:58.760 --> 00:11:01.710
Our experience has to feel
just like one experience.

00:11:01.710 --> 00:11:05.460
And so by making all layouts
look and feel the same, you

00:11:05.460 --> 00:11:08.540
have this transitional point,
for example, that feels really

00:11:08.540 --> 00:11:10.050
natural and smooth.

00:11:10.050 --> 00:11:13.130
For example, in the books
application, we have a set of

00:11:13.130 --> 00:11:14.800
recommendations at the bottom.

00:11:14.800 --> 00:11:16.920
And when you expand those
recommendations you're lending

00:11:16.920 --> 00:11:20.370
to the store, but in reality,
the view is exactly the same.

00:11:20.370 --> 00:11:24.210
So the user will just feel
like he's expanding his

00:11:24.210 --> 00:11:24.630
collection.

00:11:24.630 --> 00:11:26.680
He wants to see all the elements
present in the

00:11:26.680 --> 00:11:26.945
collection.

00:11:26.945 --> 00:11:30.500
And he won't necessarily think
about now I just landed into a

00:11:30.500 --> 00:11:31.750
different APK.

00:11:31.750 --> 00:11:37.030
So this allows us even to mix
our applications more and I

00:11:37.030 --> 00:11:41.990
guess creating some cross
vertical opportunities across

00:11:41.990 --> 00:11:45.266
our play applications.

00:11:45.266 --> 00:11:48.880
And finally about familiarity,
by applying the same design

00:11:48.880 --> 00:11:52.240
principles across all the play
applications for it, you

00:11:52.240 --> 00:11:56.210
basically see how we start
generating a type of brand

00:11:56.210 --> 00:12:01.670
that happens to be visible
across all of them.

00:12:01.670 --> 00:12:03.150
It's just very recognizable.

00:12:03.150 --> 00:12:06.210
It's very playful through the
varied colored action bars

00:12:06.210 --> 00:12:10.761
through this cards type of
metaphor through this grid.

00:12:10.761 --> 00:12:13.540
It really starts feeling like
something that differentiate

00:12:13.540 --> 00:12:16.700
from other applications present
out there and it feels

00:12:16.700 --> 00:12:19.790
very Googely.

00:12:19.790 --> 00:12:21.020
Now we're going to
talk about music.

00:12:21.020 --> 00:12:24.980
So I'll let Owen to continue.

00:12:24.980 --> 00:12:25.130
OWEN OTTO: Hi.

00:12:25.130 --> 00:12:27.800
Now I'm going to give you a
little walk through on how we

00:12:27.800 --> 00:12:30.570
applied some of the principles
Marco was just talking about

00:12:30.570 --> 00:12:34.180
to the design of the music
app, in specific.

00:12:34.180 --> 00:12:37.600
And I wanted to start with just
perhaps a provocative

00:12:37.600 --> 00:12:41.440
idea within the design
community.

00:12:41.440 --> 00:12:44.170
There's this notion that we
should be designing for mobile

00:12:44.170 --> 00:12:46.680
first that's very
popular lately.

00:12:46.680 --> 00:12:49.500
Previously, maybe people were
designing web apps and then

00:12:49.500 --> 00:12:52.210
they were kind of figuring out
how to scale them down to the

00:12:52.210 --> 00:12:56.300
phone, which we realized was a
bad idea, and maybe we should

00:12:56.300 --> 00:12:57.440
focus on the phone first.

00:12:57.440 --> 00:13:01.600
And I think where we've moved
onto as is possibly a next

00:13:01.600 --> 00:13:03.980
step in this evolution,
which is designing for

00:13:03.980 --> 00:13:06.140
everything at once.

00:13:06.140 --> 00:13:09.330
So as Marco mentioned, we were
thinking about not just the

00:13:09.330 --> 00:13:12.630
phone, but the seven inch tablet
and the 10 inch tablet

00:13:12.630 --> 00:13:13.470
and the web.

00:13:13.470 --> 00:13:17.720
And even in music's
case, the TV.

00:13:17.720 --> 00:13:22.530
So practically speaking, one
trick that we used to approach

00:13:22.530 --> 00:13:26.610
this problem is we found that
if we, on a first pass, we

00:13:26.610 --> 00:13:30.450
kind of think about the phone
in portrait and the 10 inch

00:13:30.450 --> 00:13:34.180
tablet in landscape, that this
sort of stretches the design

00:13:34.180 --> 00:13:36.940
and really makes us think
through things

00:13:36.940 --> 00:13:38.960
in a way that scales.

