So I'm going to give you a
little demo of the music app

00:13:42.240 --> 00:13:46.730
with a phone in portrait and
the tablet in landscape.

00:13:46.730 --> 00:13:48.540
And I'll talk about these
principles that Marco was

00:13:48.540 --> 00:13:50.950
mentioning as well as just
showing you some cool things

00:13:50.950 --> 00:13:52.980
in the music app.

00:13:52.980 --> 00:13:54.670
So this is our Listen
Now page.

00:13:54.670 --> 00:13:57.600
It's sort of the home
screen in the app.

00:13:57.600 --> 00:14:01.050
The basic idea of this is when
you have a music subscription

00:14:01.050 --> 00:14:03.260
service and you suddenly have
millions of tracks at your

00:14:03.260 --> 00:14:05.640
fingertips, it can be
a little daunting to

00:14:05.640 --> 00:14:07.110
figure out what to play.

00:14:07.110 --> 00:14:09.596
So this screen tries to
be your concierge.

00:14:09.596 --> 00:14:13.570
It knows your taste and tries
to pick what you may want to

00:14:13.570 --> 00:14:16.010
play next to make this easy.

00:14:16.010 --> 00:14:19.760
And this really shows the grid
system that Marco was talking

00:14:19.760 --> 00:14:23.380
about and how it scales and
solves the problem on both the

00:14:23.380 --> 00:14:25.480
phone and the tablet.

00:14:29.260 --> 00:14:32.950
So what you see here is we have
a two column grid on the

00:14:32.950 --> 00:14:40.790
phone and the five column grid
on the tablet, as well as

00:14:40.790 --> 00:14:42.100
different card sizes.

00:14:42.100 --> 00:14:45.260
There's a sort of small or
medium sized card on the phone

00:14:45.260 --> 00:14:48.610
with a Daft Punk at the top and
this very large card on

00:14:48.610 --> 00:14:49.830
the tablet.

00:14:49.830 --> 00:14:53.760
And it just brings a familiar
experience to the user between

00:14:53.760 --> 00:14:57.120
both form factors, as well as
making it easier for us to

00:14:57.120 --> 00:15:00.160
design and easier for engineers
to implement when we

00:15:00.160 --> 00:15:02.015
reuse these grids and
card systems.

00:15:04.550 --> 00:15:07.560
Next I wanted to show you what
an artist page looks like.

00:15:07.560 --> 00:15:09.580
So this is the page
for She and Him.

00:15:09.580 --> 00:15:11.980
They have a new album out now.

00:15:11.980 --> 00:15:15.680
And the thing that we thought
was really interesting in this

00:15:15.680 --> 00:15:18.900
layout here is in opposition
to a kind of

00:15:18.900 --> 00:15:20.880
typical tablet layout.

00:15:20.880 --> 00:15:24.130
Like imagine in a Gmail app
where you have sort of one

00:15:24.130 --> 00:15:27.220
column that has all of the
messages and on the right is

00:15:27.220 --> 00:15:30.340
sort of an expansion of
one of those messages.

00:15:30.340 --> 00:15:32.780
We decided to go over here on
the tablet where we really

00:15:32.780 --> 00:15:38.230
stick with just one panel, but
we make the graphics really

00:15:38.230 --> 00:15:41.600
large and beautiful
and immersive.

00:15:41.600 --> 00:15:46.375
As well as by using the cluster
layout, the same one

00:15:46.375 --> 00:15:48.110
that I was talking about before
in the Listen Now

00:15:48.110 --> 00:15:53.830
screen, you can scale up to
fill the page nicely.

00:15:53.830 --> 00:15:57.430
You can also see in action on
this page the cluster model

00:15:57.430 --> 00:15:59.370
that we were talking about
before that's spread out

00:15:59.370 --> 00:16:02.380
throughout all the Play apps
where you can have different

00:16:02.380 --> 00:16:06.080
sections, in this case related
artists, and you can expand

00:16:06.080 --> 00:16:07.330
them to get to more.

00:16:12.540 --> 00:16:16.810
Next I want to show you
our playlist screen.

00:16:16.810 --> 00:16:19.040
One of the really cool things
we have in the service is we

00:16:19.040 --> 00:16:23.720
actually have a team of editors
who are sitting around

00:16:23.720 --> 00:16:26.450
making these awesome playlists,
things like--

00:16:26.450 --> 00:16:29.100
I like this one called Intro
to Nordic Metal.

00:16:29.100 --> 00:16:31.090
So you can learn about new
genres you don't know anything

00:16:31.090 --> 00:16:35.240
about or keep up to date on a
genre that you're really into.

00:16:35.240 --> 00:16:37.080
This is one I've been listening
to lately that's on

00:16:37.080 --> 00:16:39.160
Indy Electronic.

00:16:39.160 --> 00:16:42.780
One of the really nice things
that we came up with on this

00:16:42.780 --> 00:16:45.680
page was we wanted to continue
that design that I was showing

00:16:45.680 --> 00:16:47.880
on the artist page where we have
a big immersive graphic

00:16:47.880 --> 00:16:48.740
at the top.

00:16:48.740 --> 00:16:50.270
But when we got to the playlist
page, we were like,

00:16:50.270 --> 00:16:52.290
what do we do because the
artist, there's a lot of

00:16:52.290 --> 00:16:53.730
artists on this page?

00:16:53.730 --> 00:16:55.860
And we struck upon the idea
of just doing this kind of

00:16:55.860 --> 00:16:58.120
rotating carousel.

00:16:58.120 --> 00:17:02.200
So you can see on many different
artists photos from

00:17:02.200 --> 00:17:03.940
all the songs that are
in the playlist.

00:17:08.510 --> 00:17:12.810
Another interesting thing here
about the relationship between

00:17:12.810 --> 00:17:16.280
the phone and the tablet in
landscape is you can see over

00:17:16.280 --> 00:17:19.380
here on the song list on the
tablet, we've got a little bit

00:17:19.380 --> 00:17:20.440
more room here.

00:17:20.440 --> 00:17:24.130
So rather than showing the song
title and the artist name

00:17:24.130 --> 00:17:27.670
right next to each other as we
do on the phone, we spread

00:17:27.670 --> 00:17:30.160
them out into separate columns
on the tablet.

00:17:30.160 --> 00:17:32.430
And you can also bring in a
little bit more information on

00:17:32.430 --> 00:17:35.060
the tablet like the song
duration, which just doesn't

00:17:35.060 --> 00:17:38.890
really fit nicely
on the phone.

00:17:38.890 --> 00:17:42.870
Another example of this same
kind of principle is in our

00:17:42.870 --> 00:17:45.610
Now Playing bar which you see
at the bottom of both the

00:17:45.610 --> 00:17:48.640
phone and the tablet, which
shows you the currently

00:17:48.640 --> 00:17:52.610
playing song and gives
you a few controls.

00:17:52.610 --> 00:17:55.730
Now on the phone where there's
not a lot of space, we just

00:17:55.730 --> 00:17:58.330
have a play button in addition
to the song info.

00:17:58.330 --> 00:18:01.760
But on the tablet, we give you
a full previous button and

00:18:01.760 --> 00:18:04.470
next button and even thumbs up
and thumbs down so you can do

00:18:04.470 --> 00:18:05.650
some rating.

00:18:05.650 --> 00:18:10.570
So it's just that you can take
the same elements and just add

00:18:10.570 --> 00:18:13.020
a little bit more
on the tablet.

00:18:13.020 --> 00:18:15.860
But you still maintain that
consistency and reusing the

00:18:15.860 --> 00:18:19.770
same components from an
engineering perspective.

00:18:19.770 --> 00:18:21.880
ROMAN NURIK: One of things I
wanted to call out really

00:18:21.880 --> 00:18:26.280
quickly is that this isn't
like two separate apps.

00:18:26.280 --> 00:18:29.300
Throughout this entire
presentation or demo so far

00:18:29.300 --> 00:18:32.146
you guys have basically been
showing the same app on a

00:18:32.146 --> 00:18:32.920
phone and a tablet.

00:18:32.920 --> 00:18:36.150
It's just that the individual
elements in the app, the

00:18:36.150 --> 00:18:39.240
individual elements within the
Now Playing bar and within the

00:18:39.240 --> 00:18:42.170
kind of song list, those stretch
and those kind of

00:18:42.170 --> 00:18:44.610
realign themselves or
position themselves.

00:18:44.610 --> 00:18:46.600
That's one of my favorite things
about this app is that

00:18:46.600 --> 00:18:48.600
it's truly a responsive
design at the

00:18:48.600 --> 00:18:50.620
individual component level.

00:18:50.620 --> 00:18:51.140
OWEN OTTO: Yeah.

00:18:51.140 --> 00:18:52.390
That's really important
to our approach.

00:18:55.060 --> 00:18:58.650
A couple other things
I wanted to mention.

00:18:58.650 --> 00:19:02.190
One cool thing we did on the
phone because we didn't have

00:19:02.190 --> 00:19:05.690
room for those next and previous
buttons, we have

00:19:05.690 --> 00:19:08.910
these little touches like you
can swipe to go the next song.

00:19:12.260 --> 00:19:13.460
It's pretty cool.

00:19:13.460 --> 00:19:16.220
And the next piece I want
to talk about is

00:19:16.220 --> 00:19:17.470
our Now Playing screen.

00:19:20.600 --> 00:19:23.080
This, again, shows the idea we
were talking about before

00:19:23.080 --> 00:19:28.730
where the same design when you
have these large graphics,

00:19:28.730 --> 00:19:31.070
scales to both form factors.

00:19:31.070 --> 00:19:33.460
Maybe the graphic gets cropped
a little bit differently, but

00:19:33.460 --> 00:19:35.550
it still is beautiful
and immersive.

00:19:38.430 --> 00:19:42.020
And again, you can swipe to go
to the next track on the Now

00:19:42.020 --> 00:19:42.580
Playing screen.

00:19:42.580 --> 00:19:46.210
It's pretty nice.

00:19:46.210 --> 00:19:50.220
The last piece I wanted to talk
about is our Queue UI.

00:19:50.220 --> 00:19:54.720
This is where you can see what
songs are coming up next.

00:19:54.720 --> 00:19:58.140
And here there's some
other nice gestures.

00:19:58.140 --> 00:20:02.950
You can swipe to remove songs if
you don't want to hear one.

00:20:02.950 --> 00:20:05.440
Now on the tablet, we did a
nice little touch to just

00:20:05.440 --> 00:20:09.140
customize for the tablet and use
this space well, which is

00:20:09.140 --> 00:20:11.600
just that rather than making
this be a full screen like it

00:20:11.600 --> 00:20:16.910
is on the phone, the queue, we
made it just be a pop up.

00:20:16.910 --> 00:20:20.593
So you can still stay in your
Now Playing screen without

00:20:20.593 --> 00:20:22.370
kind of having to leave
to go somewhere else.

00:20:26.060 --> 00:20:30.730
So that's the basic idea is to
design for the phone and

00:20:30.730 --> 00:20:33.260
tablet and think about
all the other

00:20:33.260 --> 00:20:35.170
screens at the same time.

00:20:35.170 --> 00:20:38.810
And a lot of these components
can be reused and scale with

00:20:38.810 --> 00:20:44.140
just slight tweaks to optimize
for the form factor.

00:20:44.140 --> 00:20:44.560
NICK BUTCHER: All right.

00:20:44.560 --> 00:20:45.030
Excellent.

00:20:45.030 --> 00:20:47.040
Thank you very much for
going through that.

00:20:47.040 --> 00:20:51.210
That's a brilliant whirlwind
tour of cards philosophy

00:20:51.210 --> 00:20:54.400
behind Google Play and
how to apply it.

00:20:54.400 --> 00:20:57.230
I had a few questions I
wanted to pick up on.

00:20:57.230 --> 00:21:01.340
So you said you're trying to
think about all devices at

00:21:01.340 --> 00:21:02.410
once when you're designing.

00:21:02.410 --> 00:21:04.600
Practically, how do you
go about doing that?

00:21:04.600 --> 00:21:08.320
I mean, do you have a large
canvas with all the different

00:21:08.320 --> 00:21:10.230
screen sizes all at once?

00:21:10.230 --> 00:21:11.480
How do you actually go
about doing this?

00:21:14.800 --> 00:21:15.170
OWEN OTTO: You want
me to take that?

00:21:15.170 --> 00:21:17.040
MARCO PAGLIA: Sure.

00:21:17.040 --> 00:21:19.910
OWEN OTTO: So I think one tact
is the one I was mentioning

00:21:19.910 --> 00:21:25.500
which is when we're going in
deep on a design, we may think

00:21:25.500 --> 00:21:28.860
we may narrow the scope down
at first to the phone in

00:21:28.860 --> 00:21:32.000
portrait and a tablet
in landscape.

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:39.750
But I think another key piece is
that we worked on the Store

00:21:39.750 --> 00:21:44.180
app everywhere in great
detail at first.

00:21:44.180 --> 00:21:48.000
So this allowed us to then learn
a lot about the patterns

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:50.090
and how they work on the
different form factors, and we

00:21:50.090 --> 00:21:51.980
could bring that back
to each of the

00:21:51.980 --> 00:21:53.550
different vertical apps.

00:21:53.550 --> 00:21:53.780
MARCO PAGLIA: Yeah.

00:21:53.780 --> 00:21:57.580
There's a lot to say about a
good technique for having a

00:21:57.580 --> 00:22:00.240
suite of applications
to be consistent.

00:22:00.240 --> 00:22:04.300
To basically reinvest on one
first in order to get to learn

00:22:04.300 --> 00:22:07.980
all the lessons that needs to be
learned and to do the best

00:22:07.980 --> 00:22:09.100
tweaks on the layouts.

00:22:09.100 --> 00:22:11.525
And then sort of expand that
to other applications.

00:22:11.525 --> 00:22:14.850
There's a lot of code that
can be re-utilized.

00:22:14.850 --> 00:22:16.770
And that becomes very useful.

00:22:16.770 --> 00:22:19.360
We're actually moving into a
space where we try to make

00:22:19.360 --> 00:22:22.310
those components more a
part of the framework.

00:22:22.310 --> 00:22:25.360
And that will be the ultimate
goal, to really have these

00:22:25.360 --> 00:22:28.860
components to be called by any
Play application and just

00:22:28.860 --> 00:22:31.290
inherit a lot of properties.

00:22:31.290 --> 00:22:34.240
From the design side, I wish you
could come to our office,

00:22:34.240 --> 00:22:35.950
because it's pretty
interesting to

00:22:35.950 --> 00:22:37.260
see the way we work.

00:22:37.260 --> 00:22:40.260
Most the time you see people,
for example, working on

00:22:40.260 --> 00:22:43.140
Illustrator and multiple
canvases representing phones

00:22:43.140 --> 00:22:46.420
and tablets next to each other
and just copy and pasting

00:22:46.420 --> 00:22:49.090
elements from one another,
see if they work.

00:22:49.090 --> 00:22:51.590
I think it's very important from
a design perspective to

00:22:51.590 --> 00:22:55.410
have tools that allows you to
see things at the same time to

00:22:55.410 --> 00:22:56.980
support canvases.

00:22:56.980 --> 00:23:00.230
And I think a lot of
applications that we use today

00:23:00.230 --> 00:23:04.382
have made great progress
allowing for that.

00:23:04.382 --> 00:23:05.850
NICK BUTCHER: Cool.

00:23:05.850 --> 00:23:07.710
ROMAN NURIK: One of the
questions I had was in terms

00:23:07.710 --> 00:23:10.990
of how you communicate
with engineers.

00:23:10.990 --> 00:23:14.090
So this is actually something
that we've covered before.

00:23:14.090 --> 00:23:17.600
We've covered this when Alex
Faaborg from your team joined

00:23:17.600 --> 00:23:19.690
us, but just wanted
to get your take.

00:23:19.690 --> 00:23:23.100
So during the process of
designing the Google Play

00:23:23.100 --> 00:23:26.950
client apps as well as the
Google Play music app, can you

00:23:26.950 --> 00:23:29.760
share any tips and tricks or
anything like that from the

00:23:29.760 --> 00:23:31.910
process of working with
the engineering team?

00:23:34.410 --> 00:23:36.620
MARCO PAGLIA: So one important
thing for us

00:23:36.620 --> 00:23:38.890
is to be very specific.

00:23:38.890 --> 00:23:43.140
So skipping all the details
about how we get to design

00:23:43.140 --> 00:23:44.960
those applications in the
first place and all the

00:23:44.960 --> 00:23:49.180
creativity that goes into it,
but focusing on the specs, if

00:23:49.180 --> 00:23:51.690
you wish, which is where
we have a very tight

00:23:51.690 --> 00:23:52.470
collaboration with

00:23:52.470 --> 00:23:57.180
engineering, we make red lines.

00:23:57.180 --> 00:24:03.590
We make a lot of very detailed
specifications because it's

00:24:03.590 --> 00:24:05.530
very important to
produce mocks.

00:24:05.530 --> 00:24:09.630
And it's very important to
define all paddings, all phone

00:24:09.630 --> 00:24:13.600
sizes, everything that is
necessary to make this layout

00:24:13.600 --> 00:24:15.490
to be the way we
want it to be.

00:24:15.490 --> 00:24:20.150
But like I said before, if you
have these modular places in

00:24:20.150 --> 00:24:24.020
mind, it's really important to
get to a very precise level,

00:24:24.020 --> 00:24:26.600
the finish in the first time,
but after that, it's done.

00:24:26.600 --> 00:24:29.250
There's a lot of code that
can be shared afterwards.

00:24:29.250 --> 00:24:33.070
So what happened is that we
had to produce a lot of

00:24:33.070 --> 00:24:36.230
guidelines and specifications,
especially for the Store which

00:24:36.230 --> 00:24:37.880
shaped first.

00:24:37.880 --> 00:24:41.110
But after that, we managed to
have engineering to be talking

00:24:41.110 --> 00:24:44.390
to each other and get a lot of
that information almost for

00:24:44.390 --> 00:24:46.695
free which which was
very important.

00:24:49.300 --> 00:24:52.310
NICK BUTCHER: Is that another
example of your inside out

00:24:52.310 --> 00:24:54.340
rather than an outside
in approach?

00:24:54.340 --> 00:24:57.720
So by going deep and working on
the Play Store and defining

00:24:57.720 --> 00:24:59.920
detailed red lines for different
sizes of elements,

00:24:59.920 --> 00:25:02.495
you were then just able
to say use the same--

00:25:02.495 --> 00:25:02.800
MARCO PAGLIA: Yes.

00:25:02.800 --> 00:25:03.506
NICK BUTCHER: --as well?

00:25:03.506 --> 00:25:03.860
MARCO PAGLIA: Yes.

00:25:03.860 --> 00:25:04.690
Yes.

00:25:04.690 --> 00:25:06.160
Exactly.

00:25:06.160 --> 00:25:11.450
And about the communication,
documents are never enough and

00:25:11.450 --> 00:25:12.410
they keep on changing.

00:25:12.410 --> 00:25:16.740
So we also have a specific
website which is where we post

00:25:16.740 --> 00:25:19.680
all our materials and they
are more accessible.

00:25:19.680 --> 00:25:22.870
And this is where engineering
can go and get all the

00:25:22.870 --> 00:25:24.150
information that they need.

00:25:24.150 --> 00:25:31.160
Plus, we are lucky, we work next
to the engineering team.

00:25:31.160 --> 00:25:33.640
We are part of the same team.

00:25:33.640 --> 00:25:35.040
We're in the same building.

00:25:35.040 --> 00:25:39.450
And so nothing can be better
than face to face of course.

00:25:39.450 --> 00:25:44.190
It's obviously very hard to
get to the right level of

00:25:44.190 --> 00:25:47.080
specification by simply writing
documents, especially

00:25:47.080 --> 00:25:50.090
when you get to motion design
and all those nuances that

00:25:50.090 --> 00:25:54.220
Owen has shown like the playlist
design if you don't

00:25:54.220 --> 00:25:56.960
sit next to each other.

00:25:56.960 --> 00:25:59.375
OWEN OTTO: I think one other
thing I'd add that applies

00:25:59.375 --> 00:26:01.960
that we really did in the Google
Play redesign and just

00:26:01.960 --> 00:26:07.060
applies to working with
engineers in general is to get

00:26:07.060 --> 00:26:10.170
the engineers involved really
early in the process.

00:26:10.170 --> 00:26:14.680
So I started meeting with
engineers and presenting when

00:26:14.680 --> 00:26:18.010
we just had really rough
sketches of the information

00:26:18.010 --> 00:26:21.690
architecture and kind of a rough
idea of how different

00:26:21.690 --> 00:26:25.810
features would work, not
beautiful mocks, not things

00:26:25.810 --> 00:26:28.520
were red lined out or anything,
but just kind of the

00:26:28.520 --> 00:26:29.830
rough strokes.

00:26:29.830 --> 00:26:34.090
And through that, we get
everyone's feedback early on

00:26:34.090 --> 00:26:37.750
and also learn about things that
might be technical issues

00:26:37.750 --> 00:26:40.680
that we might want to work
around in the design or tweak

00:26:40.680 --> 00:26:43.479
to make sure that we have a
really good user experience at

00:26:43.479 --> 00:26:44.729
the end of the day.

00:26:46.914 --> 00:26:48.420
ROMAN NURIK: Thanks.

00:26:48.420 --> 00:26:50.920
NICK BUTCHER: I want to ask
a quick question about the

